<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALBUM REVIEWS; 
</P>
<P>
**** CHARLES LLOYD "FISH OUT OF WATER" ECM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BILL KOHLHAASE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On this contemplative, sometimes ethereal recording, his first for ECM, 
saxophonist-flutist Charles Lloyd, who tends to look inward for musical 
direction, reaches a transcendent plateau, interweaving his interest in things 
spiritual with the bluesy roots of his native Memphis. 
</P>
<P>
It's this Memphis connection that keeps the session from developing into New 
Age atmospherics as Lloyd plays searching, sometimes Coltrane-flavored tenor 
with plenty of subtle bluesy touches, all in an airy, understated way. 
</P>
<P>
His flute work on "Tellaro," isn't as successful; though meditative enough, it 
too often approaches Paul Horn-ish banality. Pianist Bobo Stenson, bassist 
Palle Danielsson and drummer Jon Christensen sound remarkably similar to trios 
led by pianist Keith Jarrett, the pianist from the original Lloyd Quartet. BILL 
KOHLHAASE 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Charles Lloyd . . . reaches a transcendent plateau in "Fish." DOROTHY 
DARR 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
