<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP EYE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK GOLDSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TALK OF THE TOWN: So is Michael Jackson going to have a new manager or not? 
That's Topic A in record-biz circles this week, now that most execs are getting 
over their shock and dismay at seeing their names in (or not in) the dreaded 
"Hit Men" expose, which has already jumped to No. 8 on The Times' best-seller 
list. Initially, the hottest contenders were the top management duos of Stiefel 
&amp; Edwards and Lippman &amp; Kahane. 
</P>
<P>
But with L&amp;K having split up and S&amp;E involved with Prince (whom Jackson 
considers a pop rival) a new name has emerged among industry insiders as a 
leading candidate. The hot ticket? Veteran manager Sandy Gallin, who handles 
the likes of Neil Diamond, Dolly Parton and Andrew Dice Clay. Gallin is also 
considered a favorite by some observers because of his friendship with David 
Geffen, Jackson's confidante and close adviser. Meanwhile, execs at CBS 
Records, Jackson's label, are nervously awaiting an upcoming meeting with Bert 
Fields, the influential (and combative) entertainment attorney who is handling 
Jackson's renegotiations with CBS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
