<HEADLINE>
<P>
GAY-BASHING IN THE RECORD INDUSTRY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Concerning the record industry's simplistic and rather naive blanket defense of 
some of the crap it releases under "free speech" and "First Amendment" rights: 
I wish I could make millions at my job and still be able to claim immunity from 
liability. 
</P>
<P>
Even Kinson now sees his "humor" was dangerous. When will Warners get the 
message? 
</P>
<P>
JIM ROSS 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA081290-0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 260512 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 12, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 107; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
94 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GAY-BASHING IN THE RECORD INDUSTRY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Judging by the public image of many gay-bashing rock musicians, their struggle 
for masculine security continues. 
</P>
<P>
What else explains their tendency toward portraying women as phallic slaves and 
looking more confused in their gender identities than do most avowed 
homsexuals? 
</P>
<P>
Without whole men to call our youths out of an increasingly long and confused 
adolescence, the gap between homophobes (and their troubadours) and homosexuals 
will only widen. 
</P>
<P>
Gay activists swat at symptoms in attempting to silence gay-bashing rockers. 
</P>
<P>
ANDY COMISKEY 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
