<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: CAMARILLO; 
</P>
<P>
GYPSY BOOTS PUTS ON A SHOW FOR HIS 80TH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PSYCHE PASCUAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For Gypsy Boots, good-health guru of Camarillo, another day became another 
decade as the garlic-munching, football-tossing free spirit pronounced his 80th 
birthday a week early. 
</P>
<P>
"I'll always be a child," Boots said Saturday, sporting hot pink socks and 
sandals. He fielded football passes at Camarillo City Hall to prove how 
energetic he still is and proclaimed, "I love life, and I love people." 
</P>
<P>
Boots garnered unconventional fame as a regular on the early 1960s "Steve Allen 
Show," for which he was billed as the vegetarian Nature Boy. He still appears 
regularly at Los Angeles sporting events. 
</P>
<P>
Born Robert Bootzin in San Francisco in 1910, the soon-to-be octogenarian says 
he has always been a little ahead of his time. In fact, he is about eight days 
ahead; the actual date of his birthday is Aug. 19. But his birthday bash was 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
On Aug 19, he intends to have a party for his fans in Los Angeles. But to prove 
to his Ventura County friends that he is not going to neglect them, he decided 
to have two. 
</P>
<P>
What does a Nature Boy do on his birthday? He takes a one-mile jog to prove 
he's not about to give up, then eats a meal of fruit and carrot cake. About 15 
well-wishers gathered in a shopping center parking lot to greet Boots and share 
in the celebration. 
</P>
<P>
Kristin Anderson, 21, of Santa Barbara was one of four young women who 
accompanied Boots as he jogged briskly on a city street. Anderson said she and 
a friend met Boots on a beach and decided "he's quite a guy. "We were impressed 
with his whole energy." 
</P>
<P>
Boots was surrounded by a bevy of energetic female fans, a few in their 20s and 
some in the over-40 crowd. They watched him take a twirl with a belly dancer. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm 65, and he's 80, and he's in better shape than I am," said longtime friend 
Joann Brentley of Camarillo. 
</P>
<P>
Boots says the key to longevity are daily doses of garlic, baths in a cold 
stream and daily exercise. His constant smile proves that he is a truly happy 
man, he says. 
</P>
<P>
"People say to me, 'Don't you get old?' " Boots said. "I say, 'Yeah, I can't 
wait to be 1,000.' " PSYCHE PASCUAL 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Henriette Hvingelby puts Gypsy Boots' stomach muscles to the test. DEBRA 
MYRENT / For The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA081290-0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 260803 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
August 12, 1990, Sunday, Ventura County Edition 
</P>
