<P>
BEADS FROM ABROAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOAN DRAPER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WHEN TZERL SELTZER opened her ethnic-bead gallery and boutique specializing in 
African, Middle Eastern and Asian articles, she filled it with ostrich-eggshell 
and snake-vertebrae beads, amber, Austrian crystal and African trading beads. 
Soon customers were clamoring to learn how to create their own such objets 
d'art, and a class was born. 
