<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENTS: FOOD; 
</P>
<P>
USER-FRIENDLY GARLIC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLEN ALPERSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COOKS HAVE been using garlic for more than 5,000 years; and its 
heart-protecting, bacteria-fighting properties have become as well known as its 
flavor. Just as notable is garlic's aromatic calling card -- though garlic 
breath does not, in fact, originate in the mouth. 
</P>
<P>
The odor-producing components of the vegetable, called allicins, are carried by 
blood stream to the lungs, where they are expelled in the act of breathing. 
</P>
<P>
The sacrifice of social intercourse for flavor is no longer necessary. A new 
line of condiments renders the pungent plant socially benign without 
compromising culinary and healthful attributes. "We have simply added things so 
the allicins are neutralized in the digestive process before being circulated 
to the lungs," says Mr. Garlic products inventor Zain Sheriff. 
</P>
<P>
 Mr. Garlic products, which contain no chemicals or preservatives, are 
available at some Ralphs, Gelson's, Mayfair and Westward Ho markets. 
</P>
<P>
ELLEN ALPERSTEIN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Mr. Garlic products Juan Lopez 
</P>
